Problem Statement¶

Context:¶

Fantasy sports are online gaming platforms where participants draft and manage virtual teams of real professional sports players. Based on the performance of the players in the real world, players are allotted points in the fantasy sports platform every match. The objective is to create the best possible team with a fixed budget to score maximum fantasy points, and users compete against each other over an entire sports league or season. Some of these fantasy sports require actual financial investments for participation, with the chances of winning monetary rewards as well as free matchday tickets on a periodic basis.

The fantasy sports market has seen tremendous growth over the past few years, with a valuation of \$18.6 billion in 2019. The football (soccer) segment led in terms of market share in 2019, with over 8 million participants worldwide, and is expected to retain its dominance over the next couple of years. Digitalization is one of the primary factors driving the growth of the fantasy sports market as it allows participants the opportunity to compete on a global level and test their skills. With an increase in smartphone usage and availability of fantasy sports apps, this market is expected to witness a globe surge and reach a \\$48.6 billion valuation by 2027.

Objective:¶

OnSports is a fantasy sports platform that has fantasy leagues for many different sports and has witnessed an increasing number of participants globally over the past 5 years. For each player, a price is set at the start, and the price keeps changing over time based on the performance of the players in the real world. With the new English Premier League season about to start, they have collected data from the past season and want to analyze it to determine the price of each player for the start of the new season. OnSports have hired you as a data scientist and asked you to conduct a cluster analysis to identify players of different potentials of each player based on previous season performance. This will help them understand the patterns in player performances and fantasy returns and decide the exact price to be set for each player for the upcoming football season.

Data Description:¶

  • Player_Name: Name of the player.
  • Club: Club in which the player plays.
  • Position: Position in which the player plays.
  • Goals_Scored: Number of goals scored by the player in the previous season.
  • Assists: Number of passes made by the player leading to goals in the previous season.
  • Total_Points: Total number of fantasy points scored by the player in the previous season.
  • Minutes: Number of minutes played by the player in the previous season.
  • Goals_Conceded: Number of goals conceded by the player in the previous season.
  • Creativity: A score, computed using a range of stats, that assesses player performance in terms of producing goalscoring opportunities for other players.
  • Influence: A score, computed using a range of stats, that evaluates a player's impact on a match, taking into account actions that could directly or indirectly affect the match outcome.
  • Threat: A score, computed using a range of stats, that gauges players who are most likely to score goals.
  • Bonus: Total bonus points received. The three best performing players in each match receive additional bonus points based on a score computed using a range of stats. 3 points are awarded to the highest scoring player, 2 to the second best, and 1 to the third.
  • Clean_Sheets: Number of matches without conceding a goal in the previous season.

def hist_box(df, feature, kde = False, bin = None): #Here we set the kde to be False by default and bin to be none by default
  #Create a subplot with 2 rows and 1 column
  fig,ax = plt.subplots(2,1,
                      sharex=True, #Makes the suboplot share their x axis
                      gridspec_kw = {'height_ratios':(1,3)}, #Sets the height ratio opf the 2 subplots into 1:3
                      figsize = (9,7))
  #Creating the boxplot and set it at the first box
  sns.boxplot(data=df,
              x=feature,
              showmeans = True, #in boxplot, you can mark out the mean
              color = 'violet',
              ax = ax[0]) #Define this as the first of the subplot

  #Creating the histplot and set it at the second box
  sns.histplot(data=df,
              x = feature,
              bins = bin,
              kde = kde,
              ax = ax[1]) #The second boxplot

  #Adding a line into the histogram to mark out the mean
  ax[1].axvline(df[feature].mean(), #This command will create a vertical line, and the x value is at the mean
                linestyle = '--',
                color = 'green')

  #Adding a line into the histogram to mark out the median
  ax[1].axvline(df[feature].median(),#This command will create a vertical line, and the x value is at the median
                linestyle = '-.',
                color = 'black')

Creating a function to automate above¶

In [ ]:
def labeled_barplot(data,feature,perc = False, n = None):
  total = len(data[feature])
  count = data[feature].nunique()

  #Changing size of the plot
  if n is None:
    plt.figure(figsize = (count + 1, 5)) #if n is not specified, then the size of the chart will be the according to number of features
  else:
    plt.figure(figsize = (n + 1, 5))

  #Rotate the x labels
  plt.xticks(rotation = 90, fontsize = 15)

  #Create the countplot and assigning it to object
  ax = sns.countplot(data = data,
                     x = feature,
                     palette = "Paired",
                     order = data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),)

  #Creating the labels
  for p in ax.patches:
    if perc == True:
      label = "{:.1f}%".format(100*p.get_height()/total) #Gets the percentage value of the height
    else:
      label = p.get_height() # Just get the height without percentage

    #Getting coordinates for the annotation
    x = p.get_x() + p.get_width()/2
    y = p.get_height()

    #Coding the annotations
    ax.annotate(label,(x,y),
                ha = "center",
                va = "center",
                size = 12,
                xytext = (0,5),
                textcoords = "offset points")

  plt.show()

K-Means Clustering¶

Elbow Method¶

In [ ]:
#Create an empty dictionary to store the WCSS for each value of k
WCSS = {}

#Find the WCSS value for each value of k using the function
for k in range(1, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k,random_state=1).fit(pca_df) #Creating the Kmeans clustering from data_scaled using K clusters with a fixed randomness
    WCSS[k] = kmeans.inertia_ #Intertia is the WCSS

#Plot the Elbow
plt.figure()
plt.plot(list(WCSS.keys()), list(WCSS.values()), 'bx-')
plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")
plt.ylabel("WCSS")
plt.show()

Silhouette Score¶

In [ ]:
sc = {}

for k in range(2, 10):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=1).fit(pca_df)
    labels = kmeans.predict(pca_df)
    sc[k] = silhouette_score(pca_df,labels)

#Plot the Elbow
plt.figure()
plt.plot(list(sc.keys()), list(sc.values()), 'bx-')
plt.xlabel("Number of cluster")
plt.ylabel("Silhouette Score")
plt.show()

Based on the Silhouette Score, 4 clusters seem to be the optimal point. So we will choose K as 4 for this K-means

475 rows 4 columns

  • In the first row, it is saying that row 69 and row 335 are the closest together.
  • These 2 nodes form one cluster, and that cluster is now row number 476, which is the (original maximum number of rows) + 1
  • In the second row, row 396 is now closest to the cluster 476, so now these 2 forms a cluster, making a cluster of 3 members
  • This keeps happening, making all the closest clusters togetherm until all the points are one cluster.

Training different types hierarchical model on one trainng data¶

Cophenetic Correlation¶

  • It is a measure of how well the dendrogram created by the hierarchical clustering represents the dissimilarities between data points
  • A higher value would mean it is very good at representing the real data
In [ ]:
c, c_dist = cophenet(z, pdist(pca_df)) #This will give us the cophenetic correleation value and the dendrogramatic distance

#The cophenetic correlation can also be calculated by using this code: np.corrcoef(c_dist,pdist(pca_df))

Training other models of hierarchical clustering¶

  • We train different hierarchical clustering by changin the variables to the linkage code
  • Which is the distance and method.
In [ ]:
#List down the different distance options
distance_= ['euclidean',
            'chebyshev',
            'mahalanobis']

#List down the different method options
linkage_ = ['single',
            'complete',
            'average'] #Ward is not used here because it only works for euclidean distances

#Finding the option combination that gives the maximum Cophenetic Correlation

#Define a smallest possib le number first
c_max = -float('inf')

for i in distance_:
  for j in linkage_:

    z = pd.DataFrame(linkage(pca_df, metric = i, method= j))
    c, c_dist = cophenet(z, pdist(pca_df))
    print(i,j,c)

    if c > c_max:
      c_max = c #Replace the c_max value if the current cophenetic correlation is larger.
      index_max = (i,j) #note down the method and distance options for this cophenetic correlation

print('Best combination is: ', index_max)
print('Highest cophenetic correlation is: ', c_max)

DBSCAN Model Tuning¶

We change the variable and find out the silhouette score. Silhouette Score finds out how good the clustering is by looking at the within and inter-group distances

In [ ]:
#Write out the list of epsilon
eps_ = [0.5,1,2,3,4,5]

#write out the list of min_samples
min_s = [3,5,10,15,20]

#Define a max score value to find the max score
max_score = -float('inf')

for i in eps_:
  for j in min_s:

    model_dbs = DBSCAN(eps = i, min_samples = j).fit(pca_df)
    print(np.unique(model_dbs.labels_)) # To show us how many clusters are there

    #Calculating the silhouette score if there are clustering
    if len(np.unique(model_dbs.labels_)) > 1:

      score = silhouette_score(pca_df,model_dbs.labels_)
      print(score)

      #Finding hte max score
      if score > max_score:
        max_score = score
        idx_max = [i,j]
print(f'Best combination is {idx_max}')

Model Comparison¶

We can compare the performance of the different clustering techniques using the silhouette score

In [ ]:
models_ = [model_kmeans,model_kmedoids, model_agg, model_gmm, model_dbs]

for i in models_:
  try:
    score = silhouette_score(pca_df,i.predict(pca_df))
  except:
    score = silhouette_score(pca_df,i.labels_)
  print(f'The Silhouette Score for {i} is {score}.')

The Silhouette Score for KMeans(n_clusters=4, random_state=0) is 0.40409310663893694.
The Silhouette Score for KMedoids(n_clusters=4, random_state=0) is 0.3938224989846948.
The Silhouette Score for AgglomerativeClustering(affinity='euclidean', n_clusters=4) is 0.38497099800605145.
The Silhouette Score for GaussianMixture(n_components=4, random_state=0) is 0.2849464415241945.
The Silhouette Score for DBSCAN(eps=4, min_samples=15) is 0.6626466090568284.
